0":"13 January 1600","1382":"1382","1437":"1437","1404":"1404","1348":"1348","Abt 1366":"about 1366","about 1437":"about 1437","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1366":"1366","1475":"1475","1320":"1320","about 1345":"about 1345","1417":"1417","Sockbridge, Westmorland, England":"Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England","Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England":"Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England","Hartsop, Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lancaster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lancaster in northwestern England, which is recorded as <i>Loncastre</i> in 1086. The place takes its name from the river Lune + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘city, Roman fortification’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’). The river name is probably British, perhaps related to Gaelic <i>slán</i> ‘healthy’, ‘salubrious’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":110,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Lancaster Knt. was born about 1345, in Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England, his father, Gilbert Lancaster, was 26 and his mother, Elizabeth Lancaster, was 24. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret Strickland."},"et":{"about 1345–":"umbes 1345–Surnud","1345–Male":"1345–Surnud","1417–Female":"1417–Surnud","1348–Female":"1348–Surnud","1366–1404":"1366–1404","1437–1475":"1437–1475","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1322–Female":"1322–Surnud","WILL PROVED 13JAN1600":"13. jaanuar 1600","1382":"1382","1437":"1437","1404":"1404","1348":"1348","Abt 1366":"umbes 1366","about 1437":"umbes 1437","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1366":"1366","1475":"1475","1320":"1320","about 1345":"umbes 1345","1417":"1417","Sockbridge, Westmorland, England":"Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England","Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England":"Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England","Hartsop, Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England"},"fi":{"about 1345–":"noin 1345–Kuollut","1345–Male":"1345–Kuollut","1417–Female":"1417–Kuollut","1348–Female":"1348–Kuollut","1366–1404":"1366–1404","1437–1475":"1437–1475","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1322–Female":"1322–Kuollut","WILL PROVED 13JAN1